HOUSE BILL 577
E1 6lr1037
CF SB 334
By: Delegates Williams, Coley, Embry, Ivey, Lopez, Moreno, Pasteur, Phillips,
Ruff, Simmons, Simpson, Taylor, Toles, and Young
Introduced and read first time: January 28, 2026
Assigned to: Judiciary
Committee Report: Favorable with amendments
House action: Adopted
Read second time: March 20, 2026
CHAPTER ______
1 AN ACT concerning
2 Criminal Law – Firearm Crimes – Machine Gun Convertible Pistols
3 FOR the purpose of prohibiting, on or after a certain date, a person from manufacturing,
4 selling, offering for sale, purchasing, receiving, or transferring a certain machine gun
5 convertible pistol, subject to certain exceptions; and generally relating to firearm
6 crimes.
7 BY repealing and reenacting, without amendments,
8 Article – Criminal Law
9 Section 4–301(a) and 4–306
10 Annotated Code of Maryland
11 (2021 Replacement Volume and 2025 Supplement)
12 BY adding to
13 Article – Criminal Law
14 Section 4–301(m) and (n) 4–301(h), (j), (o), and (p) and 4–305.2
15 Annotated Code of Maryland
16 (2021 Replacement Volume and 2025 Supplement)
17 BY repealing and reenacting, with amendments,
18 Article – Criminal Law
19 Section 4–301(m) 4–301(h) through (o) and 4–302
20 Annotated Code of Maryland
21 (2021 Replacement Volume and 2025 Supplement)
EXPLANATION: CAPITALS INDICATE MATTER ADDED TO EXISTING LAW.
[Brackets] indicate matter deleted from existing law.
Underlining indicates amendments to bill.
Strike out indicates matter stricken from the bill by amendment or deleted from the law by
amendment. *hb0577*

2 HOUSE BILL 577
1 SECTION 1. BE IT ENACTED BY THE GENERAL ASSEMBLY OF MARYLAND,
2 That the Laws of Maryland read as follows:
3 Article – Criminal Law
4 4–301.
5 (a) In this subtitle the following words have the meanings indicated.
6 (H) “COMMON HOUSEHOLD TOOL” INCLUDES A SCREWDRIVER, A PIPE
7 WRENCH, PLIERS, A HACKSAW, A CROWBAR, AN ELECTRIC DRILL, A ROTARY TOOL, A
8 HAMMER, A CHISEL, A FILE, AND A CRESCENT WRENCH.
9 [(h)] (I) (1) “Copycat weapon” means:
10 (i) a semiautomatic centerfire rifle that can accept a detachable
11 magazine and has any two of the following:
12 1. a folding stock;
13 2. a grenade launcher or flare launcher; or
14 3. a flash suppressor;
15 (ii) a semiautomatic centerfire rifle that has a fixed magazine with
16 the capacity to accept more than 10 rounds;
17 (iii) a semiautomatic centerfire rifle that has an overall length of less
18 than 29 inches;
19 (iv) a semiautomatic pistol with a fixed magazine that can accept
20 more than 10 rounds;
21 (v) a semiautomatic shotgun that has a folding stock; or
22 (vi) a shotgun with a revolving cylinder.
23 (2) “Copycat weapon” does not include an assault long gun or an assault
24 pistol.
25 (J) “CRUCIFORM TRIGGER BAR” MEANS A COMPONENT IN A
26 SEMIAUTOMATIC PISTOL THAT:
27 (1) SERVES AS A LINK BETWEEN THE TRIGGER AND THE FIRING PIN;
28 AND

HOUSE BILL 577 3
1 (2) HAS ITS SEAR INCORPORATED INTO A CROSS–SHAPED SURFACE.
2 [(i)] (K) “Detachable magazine” means an ammunition feeding device that can
3 be removed readily from a firearm without requiring disassembly of the firearm action or
4 without the use of a tool, including a bullet or cartridge.
5 [(j)] (L) “Flash suppressor” means a device that functions, or is intended to
6 function, to perceptibly reduce or redirect muzzle flash from the shooter’s field of vision.
7 [(k)] (M) “Hellfire trigger” means a device that, when installed in or attached to
8 a firearm, disengages the trigger return spring when the trigger is pulled.
9 [(l)] (N) “Licensed firearms dealer” means a person who holds a dealer’s license
10 under Title 5, Subtitle 1 of the Public Safety Article.
11 (M) (O) (1) “MACHINE GUN CONVERTIBLE PISTOL” MEANS ANY
12 SEMIAUTOMATIC PISTOL WITH A CRUCIFORM TRIGGER BAR THAT CAN BE READILY
13 CONVERTED BY HAND OR BY USING COMMON HOUSEHOLD TOOLS INTO A MACHINE
14 GUN BY THE INSTALLATION OR ATTACHMENT OF A PISTOL CONVERTER AS A
15 REPLACEMENT FOR THE SLIDE’S BACKPLATE WITHOUT ANY ADDITIONAL
16 ENGINEERING, MACHINING, OR MODIFICATION OF THE PISTOL’S TRIGGER
17 MECHANISM.
18 (2) “MACHINE GUN CONVERTIBLE PISTOL” INCLUDES A PISTOL WITH
19 A CRUCIFORM TRIGGER BAR AND A POLYMER NOTCH OR OTHER PIECE OF POLYMER
20 MOLDED INTO THE REAR OF THE PISTOL FRAME WHERE A PISTOL CONVERTER CAN
21 BE ATTACHED OR INSTALLED A SEMIAUTOMATIC PISTOL DESCRIBED UNDER
22 PARAGRAPH (1) OF THIS SUBSECTION, REGARDLESS OF WHETHER A TAB OR OTHER
23 PIECE OF MATERIAL IS LOCATED ON THE REAR PORTION OF THE PISTOL FRAME TO
24 BLOCK THE ATTACHMENT OF A PISTOL CONVERTER, IF THE TAB OR OTHER PIECE OF
25 MATERIAL CAN BE READILY REMOVED WITH A COMMON HOUSEHOLD TOOL.
26 (3) “MACHINE GUN CONVERTIBLE PISTOL” DOES NOT INCLUDE A
27 HAMMER–FIRED SEMIAUTOMATIC PISTOL OR A STRIKER–FIRED SEMIAUTOMATIC
28 PISTOL WITHOUT A CRUCIFORM TRIGGER BAR, WHICH INSTEAD HAS A TRIGGER BAR
29 THAT IS SHIELDED FROM INTERFERENCE BY A PISTOL CONVERTER.
30 (N) (P) (1) “PISTOL CONVERTER” MEANS ANY DEVICE OR INSTRUMENT
31 THAT, WHEN INSTALLED IN OR ATTACHED TO THE REAR OF THE SLIDE OF A
32 SEMIAUTOMATIC PISTOL, REPLACES THE BACKPLATE AND INTERFERES WITH THE
33 TRIGGER MECHANISM, WHICH ENABLES THE PISTOL TO SHOOT AUTOMATICALLY
34 MORE THAN ONE SHOT BY A SINGLE FUNCTION OF THE TRIGGER.

4 HOUSE BILL 577
1 (2) “PISTOL CONVERTER” INCLUDES A PISTOL CONVERTER
2 MANUFACTURED USING A THREE–DIMENSIONAL PRINTER.
3 [(m)] (O) (Q) (1) “Rapid fire activator” means any device, including a
4 removable manual or power–driven activating device, constructed so that, when installed
5 in or attached to a firearm:
6 (i) the rate at which the trigger is activated increases; or
7 (ii) the rate of fire increases.
8 (2) “Rapid fire activator” includes a bump stock, trigger crank, hellfire
9 trigger, binary trigger system, burst trigger system, switch/auto–sear, PISTOL
10 CONVERTER, or a copy or a similar device, regardless of the producer or manufacturer.
11 (3) “Rapid fire activator” does not include a semiautomatic replacement
12 trigger that improves the performance and functionality over the stock trigger.
13 [(n)] (P) (R) “Switch/auto–sear” means a device that applies force to a firearm’s
14 trigger bar to prevent it from limiting the weapon to firing only one round each time the
15 trigger is depressed.
16 [(o)] (Q) (S) “Trigger crank” means a device that, when installed in or attached to a
17 firearm, repeatedly activates the trigger of the firearm through the use of a crank, a lever,
18 or any other part that is turned in a circular motion.
19 4–302.
20 This subtitle does not apply to:
21 (1) if acting within the scope of official business, personnel of the United
22 States government or a unit of that government, members of the armed forces of the United
23 States or of the National Guard, law enforcement personnel of the State or a local unit in
24 the State, or a railroad police officer authorized under Title 3 of the Public Safety Article
25 or 49 U.S.C. § 28101;
26 (2) a firearm modified to render it permanently inoperative;
27 (3) possession, importation, manufacture, receipt for manufacture,
28 shipment for manufacture, storage, purchases, sales, and transport to or by a licensed
29 firearms dealer or manufacturer who is:
30 (i) providing or servicing an assault weapon [or], A detachable
31 magazine, OR A MACHINE GUN CONVERTIBLE PISTOL for a law enforcement unit or for
32 personnel exempted under item (1) of this section;

HOUSE BILL 577 5
1 (ii) acting to sell or transfer an assault weapon [or], A detachable
2 magazine, OR A MACHINE GUN CONVERTIBLE PISTOL to a licensed firearm dealer in
3 another state or to an individual purchaser in another state through a licensed firearms
4 dealer; or
5 (iii) acting to return to a customer in another state an assault weapon
6 OR A MACHINE GUN CONVERTIBLE PISTOL transferred to the licensed firearms dealer
7 or manufacturer under the terms of a warranty or for repair;
8 (4) organizations that are required or authorized by federal law governing
9 their specific business or activity to maintain assault weapons and applicable ammunition
10 [and], detachable magazines, AND MACHINE GUN CONVERTIBLE PISTOLS;
11 (5) the receipt of an assault weapon [or], A detachable magazine, OR A
12 MACHINE GUN CONVERTIBLE PISTOL by inheritance, and possession of the inherited
13 assault weapon [or], detachable magazine, OR MACHINE GUN CONVERTIBLE PISTOL, if
14 the decedent lawfully possessed the assault weapon [or], detachable magazine, OR
15 MACHINE GUN CONVERTIBLE PISTOL and the person inheriting the assault weapon [or],
16 detachable magazine, OR MACHINE GUN CONVERTIBLE PISTOL is not otherwise
17 disqualified from possessing a regulated firearm;
18 (6) the receipt of an assault weapon [or], A detachable magazine, OR A
19 MACHINE GUN CONVERTIBLE PISTOL by a personal representative of an estate for
20 purposes of exercising the powers and duties of a personal representative of an estate;
21 (7) possession by a person who is retired in good standing from service with
22 a law enforcement agency of the State or a local unit in the State and is not otherwise
23 prohibited from receiving an assault weapon [or], detachable magazine, OR MACHINE GUN
24 CONVERTIBLE PISTOL if:
25 (i) the assault weapon [or], detachable magazine, OR MACHINE
26 GUN CONVERTIBLE PISTOL is sold or transferred to the person by the law enforcement
27 agency on retirement; or
28 (ii) the assault weapon [or], detachable magazine, OR MACHINE
29 GUN CONVERTIBLE PISTOL was purchased or obtained by the person for official use with
30 the law enforcement agency before retirement;
31 (8) possession or transport by an employee of an armored car company if
32 the individual is acting within the scope of employment and has a permit issued under Title
33 5, Subtitle 3 of the Public Safety Article; [or]
34 (9) possession, receipt, and testing by, or shipping to or from:

6 HOUSE BILL 577
1 (i) an ISO 17025 accredited, National Institute of Justice–approved
2 ballistics testing laboratory; or
3 (ii) a facility or entity that manufactures or provides research and
4 development testing, analysis, or engineering for personal protective equipment or vehicle
5 protection systems;
6 (10) THE TEMPORARY TRANSFER OF A MACHINE GUN CONVERTIBLE
7 PISTOL TO A LICENSED REGULATED FIREARMS DEALER OR GUNSMITH FOR THE
8 PURPOSE OF SERVICING THE MACHINE GUN CONVERTIBLE PISTOL;
9 (11) THE RECEIPT OF A MACHINE GUN CONVERTIBLE PISTOL BY A
10 LICENSED REGULATED FIREARMS DEALER OR GUNSMITH FOR THE PURPOSE OF
11 SERVICING THE MACHINE GUN CONVERTIBLE PISTOL AND THE RETURN OF THE
12 MACHINE GUN CONVERTIBLE PISTOL TO ITS LAWFUL OWNER BY A LICENSED
13 REGULATED FIREARMS DEALER OR GUNSMITH ON THE COMPLETION OF SERVICING
14 THE MACHINE GUN CONVERTIBLE PISTOL; OR
15 (12) THE RECEIPT OF A MACHINE GUN CONVERTIBLE PISTOL BY A LAW
16 ENFORCEMENT UNIT, BARRACKS, OR STATION, A STATE OR LOCAL LAW
17 ENFORCEMENT AGENCY, OR A FEDERALLY LICENSED FIREARMS DEALER IF THE
18 PERSON IS SURRENDERING THE FIREARM;
19 (13) THE TEMPORARY GRATUITOUS EXCHANGE OF A MACHINE GUN
20 CONVERTIBLE PISTOL; OR
21 (14) THE SALE, OFFER FOR SALE, PURCHASE, RECEIPT, OR TRANSFER
22 OF A MACHINE GUN CONVERTIBLE PISTOL TO OR BY A PERSON WHO:
23 (I) IS CURRENTLY A LAW ENFORCEMENT OFFICIAL, AS
24 DEFINED IN § 4–201 OF THIS TITLE; OR
25 (II) HAS RETIRED AS A LAW ENFORCEMENT OFFICIAL IN GOOD
26 STANDING FROM A LAW ENFORCEMENT AGENCY OF THE UNITED STATES, THE
27 STATE OR ANOTHER STATE, OR A LOCAL UNIT IN THE STATE OR ANOTHER STATE
28 AND POSSESSES A VALID CREDENTIAL ISSUED UNDER 18 U.S.C. § 926C.
29 4–305.2.
30 (A) ON EXCEPT AS OTHERWISE PROVIDED IN THIS SECTION, ON OR AFTER
31 JANUARY 1, 2027, A PERSON MAY NOT MANUFACTURE, SELL, OFFER FOR SALE,
32 PURCHASE, RECEIVE, OR TRANSFER A MACHINE GUN CONVERTIBLE PISTOL.

HOUSE BILL 577 7
1 (B) THE DEPARTMENT OF STATE POLICE MAY ADOPT REGULATIONS TO
2 IMPLEMENT THIS SECTION, INCLUDING PUBLISHING A LIST OF PROHIBITED
3 MACHINE GUN CONVERTIBLE PISTOLS.
4 (C) (1) IN THIS SUBSECTION, “IMMEDIATE FAMILY MEMBER” MEANS A
5 SPOUSE, CHILD, STEPCHILD, PARENT, STEPPARENT, SIBLING, OR STEPSIBLING.
6 (2) (I) A PERSON WHO LAWFULLY OBTAINED AND POSSESSES A
7 MACHINE GUN CONVERTIBLE PISTOL MAY SELL OR OTHERWISE TRANSFER A
8 MACHINE GUN CONVERTIBLE PISTOL TO AN IMMEDIATE FAMILY MEMBER WHO IS
9 NOT PROHIBITED UNDER FEDERAL OR STATE LAW FROM POSSESSING A FIREARM.
10 (II) A PERSON WHO IS NOT OTHERWISE PROHIBITED UNDER
11 FEDERAL OR STATE LAW FROM POSSESSING A FIREARM MAY PURCHASE OR
12 OTHERWISE RECEIVE A MACHINE GUN CONVERTIBLE PISTOL FROM AN IMMEDIATE
13 FAMILY MEMBER WHO LAWFULLY OBTAINED THE PISTOL.
14 4–306.
15 (a) Except as otherwise provided in this subtitle, a person who violates this
16 subtitle is guilty of a misdemeanor and on conviction is subject to imprisonment not
17 exceeding 3 years or a fine not exceeding $5,000 or both.
18 (b) (1) A person who uses an assault weapon, a rapid fire activator, or a
19 magazine that has a capacity of more than 10 rounds of ammunition, in the commission of
20 a felony or a crime of violence as defined in § 5–101 of the Public Safety Article is guilty of
21 a misdemeanor and on conviction, in addition to any other sentence imposed for the felony
22 or crime of violence, shall be sentenced under this subsection.
23 (2) (i) For a first violation, the person shall be sentenced to
24 imprisonment for not less than 5 years and not exceeding 20 years.
25 (ii) The court may not impose less than the minimum sentence of 5
26 years.
27 (iii) The mandatory minimum sentence of 5 years may not be
28 suspended.
29 (iv) Except as otherwise provided in § 4–305 of the Correctional
30 Services Article, the person is not eligible for parole in less than 5 years.
31 (3) (i) For each subsequent violation, the person shall be sentenced to
32 imprisonment for not less than 10 years and not exceeding 20 years.
33 (ii) The court may not impose less than the minimum sentence of 10
34 years.

8 HOUSE BILL 577
1 (iii) A sentence imposed under this paragraph shall be consecutive to
2 and not concurrent with any other sentence imposed for the felony or crime of violence.
3 SECTION 2. AND BE IT FURTHER ENACTED, That this Act shall take effect
4 October 1, 2026.
Approved:
